  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970\n- Requires financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandates reporting of cash transactions over $10,000\n\n2. The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Established money laundering as a federal criminal offense\n- Prohibited structuring transactions to avoid reporting requirements\n\n3. The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001\n- Enhanced anti-money laundering regulations\n- Expanded reporting requirements\n- Increased penalties for money laundering\n\n4. The Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- Modernized existing anti-money laundering laws\n- Improved corporate transparency\n- Expanded enforcement capabilities\n\nAt the federal level, money laundering is primarily prosecuted under 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957, which define different types of money laundering activities and establish criminal penalties.\n\nState governments also have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws.\n\nThese statutes aim to:\n- Detect and prevent financial crimes\n- Disrupt criminal enterprises\n- Trace and seize illegally obtained funds\n- Impose criminal and civil penalties on offenders",
